How do you verify originality and avoid copyright infringement?

2 Steps / Requirements of Assignment
Implement a controlled multi-step workflow that resembles an agent loop while keeping human oversight explicit. The system should not blindly generate and apply changes without review. By the end of this lab, your Java project should behave like a small, safe version of a coding agent: it receives a task, lets the LLM request approved tools, feeds tool results back into the conversation, and stops with a final answer or a safety limit.

Define the loop stages in your README before coding. Recommended stages: intake, model request, tool-call detection, approval, tool execution, tool-result message, evaluation, final response.
Define tool schemas or tool descriptions for the Java tools you built in Lab 3. Include at least file listing, file reading, file writing, and Java test execution.
Register available tools in a dispatcher, map, or registry so that a requested tool name can be matched to the correct Java implementation.
Send the tool declarations or equivalent tool descriptions with the LLM request using your chosen API. If your API wrapper does not support native function calling, you may use a structured JSON convention, but you must document the format clearly.
Detect when the model requests a tool call. Extract the tool name and arguments.
Before executing any write or command-running tool, add a human approval checkpoint. This can be an interactive y/n prompt, a --auto-approve-readonly mode, or a documented manual review step. File reads and file listings may be allowed automatically if your risk analysis supports that choice.
Execute allowed tool calls using your Lab 3 tool implementations. Unknown tools, invalid arguments, unsafe paths, and blocked commands must produce safe error messages rather than crashes.
Append tool results back into the message history and send the updated conversation back to the model.
Repeat the loop until the model produces a final answer or until a maximum iteration limit is reached. Recommended maximum: 10-20 iterations.
Preserve artifacts from one complete workflow run. Include the user prompt, model responses, tool calls, tool outputs, approval decisions, changed files, evaluation result, and final response.
Demonstrate a complete controlled workflow using your sandbox project. A good example is: inspect the calculator project, identify a bug or missing behavior, propose a change, request approval, write the change, run tests, and report the result.
Document how to reproduce the workflow from a clean checkout.

Suggested pseudocode:
messages.add(Message.user(userPrompt));
for (int i = 0; i &lt; maxIterations; i++) {
    ModelResponse response = client.generate(messages, toolSchemas);
    messages.add(response.asMessage());

    if (!response.hasToolCall()) {
        System.out.println(response.finalText());
        break;
    }

    ToolCall call = response.toolCall();
    if (requiresApproval(call) && !approvedByHuman(call)) {
        messages.add(Message.toolResult(call.name(), "Tool call rejected by human reviewer."));
        continue;
    }

    String result = dispatcher.execute(call);
    messages.add(Message.toolResult(call.name(), result));
}
Suggested checkpoint commands:
mvn test
mvn exec:java -Dexec.args="--verbose Inspect the sandbox project and run the tests"
mvn exec:java -Dexec.args="--max-iterations 10 Fix one failing test in the sandbox project"

Add Java Dependencies
There are multiple ways to call Gemini from Java. For this course, a simple REST call is acceptable and keeps the agent architecture easy to inspect. The example below uses Java’s built-in HttpClient, plus two small libraries: one for loading .env files and one for parsing JSON.
Add these dependencies to your Maven pom.xml:
&lt;dependencies&gt;
    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;io.github.cdimascio&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;dotenv-java&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;3.0.0&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;
    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.json&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;json&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;20250517&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;
&lt;/dependencies&gt;
If your instructor provides a different Gemini Java client or starter project, follow that version instead. The important concepts are the same: load the API key safely, send a prompt, receive text, and avoid committing secrets.

Minimal Java Test Program
Create or update your Main.java file so it loads the API key and sends one hard-coded prompt to Gemini. This is only a connection test; you will make the prompt configurable in Lab 1.
import io.github.cdimascio.dotenv.Dotenv;
import org.json.JSONArray;
import org.json.JSONObject;

import java.net.URI;
import java.net.http.HttpClient;
import java.net.http.HttpRequest;
import java.net.http.HttpResponse;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Dotenv dotenv = Dotenv.configure()
                .ignoreIfMalformed()
                .ignoreIfMissing()
                .load();

        String apiKey = dotenv.get("GEMINI_API_KEY", System.getenv("GEMINI_API_KEY"));
        if (apiKey == null || apiKey.isBlank()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("GEMINI_API_KEY was not found. Add it to .env or your environment.");
        }

        String prompt = "In one paragraph, explain why clear requirements help software teams build better systems.";

        JSONObject body = new JSONObject()
                .put("contents", new JSONArray()
                        .put(new JSONObject()
                                .put("parts", new JSONArray()
                                        .put(new JSONObject().put("text", prompt)))));

        HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
                .uri(URI.create("https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models/gemini-2.5-flash:generateContent?key=" + apiKey))
                .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
                .POST(HttpRequest.BodyPublishers.ofString(body.toString()))
                .build();

        HttpClient client = HttpClient.newHttpClient();
        HttpResponse&lt;String&gt; response = client.send(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());

        if (response.statusCode() &lt; 200 || response.statusCode() &gt;= 300) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Gemini API request failed with status "
                    + response.statusCode() + ": " + response.body());
        }

        JSONObject json = new JSONObject(response.body());
        String text = json
                .getJSONArray("candidates")
                .getJSONObject(0)
                .getJSONObject("content")
                .getJSONArray("parts")
                .getJSONObject(0)
                .getString("text");

        System.out.println(text);
    }
}
